pmc Sci Rep Sci Rep 1579 scirep Scientific Reports 2045-2322 Nature Publishing Group PMC12484867 PMC12484867.1 12484867 12484867 41028016 10.1038/s41598-025-06307-z 6307 1 Article A pH-responsive nanocarrier of peanut shell carbon quantum dots as a promising delivery of doxorubicin for cancer therapy Kirubanithy Kaviyapriya Santhanam Amutha amutha1994santhanam@gmail.com https://ror.org/04jmt9361 grid.413015.2 0000 0004 0505 215X Nanobiotherapeutics Laboratory, National Centre for Nanoscience and Nanotechnology, University of Madras, 30 9 2025 2025 15 478255 33885 25 10 2024 9 6 2025 30 09 2025 02 10 2025 02 10 2025 © The Author(s) 2025 2025 https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Open Access http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0/ Carbon quantum dots (CQDs) have shown great potential for drug delivery systems due to their small size and properties. Surface functionalization of CQDs directly affects the drug conjugation and release behaviour. In this study, the peanut shell carbon quantum dots (PS-CQDs) were synthesised through the hydrothermal method. The as-synthesised PS-CQDs had blue fluorescence and functional groups of hydroxyl, carboxyl, and amine. These surface group shows that the PS-CQDs have great water solubility. The free radical scavenging efficacy was also analysed and found to be 84.7%. With an average size of 2.1 ± 0.02 nm, the PS-CQDs were functionalized with a hydrazine group and then conjugated with doxorubicin. The doxorubicin conjugated sample DOX-PS-CQDs showed pH-sensitive release of the drug. The cumulative release percentage was 55.4% at pH 7.4 and 81.4% at pH 6.5, and the release profile exhibited sustained release within 24 h. The different pH enables the PS-CQDs based nanocarrier to release the drug at tumour sites efficiently. Further, in-vitro anticancer activity was studied using these PS-CQDs based nanocarriers against the MDA MB231 cell line, and the live/dead cell screening was carried out by AO/EB staining. Thus, the doxorubicin conjugated with PS-CQDs has exhibited promising properties as a drug carrier for cancer therapy. Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1038/s41598-025-06307-z. Keywords Carbon quantum Dots Doxorubicin Drug delivery Cancer therapy Subject terms Cancer Nanoscience and technology pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © Springer Nature Limited 2025 Introduction Cancer cells cause detrimental effects to normal healthy cells, blocking the bloodstream, nutrients, and oxygen, leading to life-threatening consequences. Several methods have been implemented for the treatment of cancer, including chemotherapy, radiation therapy, immunotherapy, hormone therapy, and targeted therapy. Although such conventional treatment was promising, they have its drawbacks, such as in radiation therapy, the use of x-rays can also damage healthy cells and tissues. Whereas for chemotherapy, the drug would damage normal cells along with cancer cells. Due to a lack of specificity, this negatively affects human health. Another issue lies with the emergence of drug resistance by the cancer cells 1 2 Doxorubicin is a drug commonly used for the chemotherapy of cancer. It is utilized for the treatment of various cancers, including breast cancer, lymphomas, leukaemia, sarcomas, and ovarian cancers. It interferes with the DNA of the cancer cells through intercalation into the DNA base pairs, disrupting its normal structure. This hinders the replication and duplication process of the cancer cells, rendering them unable to repair their DNA, causing cell death 3 4 5 6 7 8 9 1 10 11 The carbon quantum dots (CQDs) have attracted much attention in recent years due to their favourable and tunable properties, such as biocompatibility, chemical inertness, photostability, refractive index, and fluorescence 1 12 13 14 15 16 17 18 19 21 8 In this study, carbon quantum dots were synthesised from peanut shells by hydrothermal method. Peanut shell was selected as a source for CQDs production due to its low cost, sustainability, and eco-friendliness. Furthermore, in this study, the surface of PS-CQDs has been modified to release the doxorubicin based on pH response. This is achieved by employing 4-hydrazinobenzoic acid (HBA) as a precursor to functionalize the hydrazine group on the surface of PS-CQDs. This enhances pH-dependent drug release after conjugating onto the functionalized surface of PS-CQDs. Doxorubicin was released much more quickly at an acidic pH than at a pH of 7.4. Since the cancer cells tends to be slightly acidic, this will ensure that the drug is released as targeted drug delivery. Further antioxidant activity was also evaluated for bare PS-CQDs and it showed significant free radical scavenging activity, proving an added benefit to the system. For targeted drug delivery, we employed the MDA-MB-231, which is a triple-negative breast cancer cell line. When ER expression is lacking, MDA-MB-231 cells are resistant to anti hormone-based therapies, including tamoxifen 22 23 Materials and methods Materials The peanuts were purchased in the local market, the shells were separated, washed, and dried at 60 °C for 48 h. The dried shells were ground into powder and sieved using a 100 mesh sieve and stored at room temperature. Glacial acetic acid (99%), dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), quinine sulphate, and NaCl were purchased from Sisco Research Laboratories (SRL). Sulphuric acid (98%), phosphate buffer saline (PBS), acridine orange (AO), ethidium bromide (EB), 2,2-Diphenyl-1-picrylhydrazyl (DPPH), 4-hydrazinobenzoic acid (HBA), Doxorubicin, 